Class UniversalXmlAdapter<UnmappableType,MappableType extends UnmappableType>

      com.edugility.jaxb.UniversalXmlAdapter<UnmappableType,MappableType>
Type Parameters:
UnmappableType - the interface type (or other type) that JAXB needs to be able to handle but can't yet
MappableType - the implementation type that JAXB can handle that implements the <B> type
public abstract class UniversalXmlAdapter<UnmappableType,MappableType extends UnmappableType>
extends XmlAdapter<MappableType,UnmappableType>

An XmlAdapter that helps JAXB handle an otherwise unbindable type when it is known that that unbindable type is implemented in a given application by one and only one bindable type.

For example, perhaps you know that in a given application all Foobar instances will in fact be Whizbang instances—a class, let's say, that is annotated with XmlRootElement (and other JAXB annotations) and implements Foobar. But you do not want to write your API in terms of Whizbangs—you want to write it in terms of Foobars. That is, you want JAXB to behave as though somehow suddenly it could handle Foobar as a type that it can express as an XML construct. (Because Foobar is an interface, JAXB cannot natively handle it.)

If though, it is truly known that in your application all instances of Foobar that JAXB will be asked to bind are actually Whizbangs—a concrete, JAXB-bindable type, then you could annotate your Foobar class with the XmlJavaTypeAdapter annotation and specify this class as the XmlAdapter implementation that would ensure that all Foobars would be treated as Whizbangs internally by JAXB.

This class is "universal" only in that it can adapt any two classes provided that one is a subtype of the other.

Note: The order of the type parameters is deliberately reversed from that of the XmlAdapter class.

Author:
Laird Nelson
See Also:
XmlAdapter, XmlJavaTypeAdapter, The Unofficial JAXB Guide's section on mapping interfaces, Blaise Doughan's article on XmlAdapter usage

Method Detail

unmarshal

public final UnmappableType unmarshal(MappableType mappableObject)
Converts the supplied mappableObject—a type that JAXB knows how to handle natively—into an instance of its supertype—which JAXB may not know how to handle natively.

This method is called when transforming an XML document into Java objects. You can think of the mappableObject parameter as representing the XML value.

This implementation simply returns the supplied mappableObject. The type parameters supplied to this class at construction time ensure that this is always a valid thing to do.

Specified by:
unmarshal in class XmlAdapter<MappableType extends UnmappableType,UnmappableType>
Parameters:
mappableObject - the object to unmarshal or deserialize; may be null
Returns:
the supplied mappableObject

marshal

public final MappableType marshal(UnmappableType unmappableObject)
Converts the supplied unmappableObject into an object that JAXB can handle natively by attempting to simply cast the supplied unmappableObject to the return type of this method.

This conversion should succeed provided that the type constraints of this class are respected.

This method is called when transforming a Java object graph into an XML document. You can think of the unmappableObject parameter as representing a Java object in the graph.

Specified by:
marshal in class XmlAdapter<MappableType extends UnmappableType,UnmappableType>
Parameters:
unmappableObject - an object that for some reason or another JAXB is incapable of handling natively; may be null
Returns:
the result of casting the supplied unmappableObject to the return type of this method
Throws:
ClassCastException - if for some reason the cast could not take place
